## Build & Package Management

- **Avoid full builds** — prefer type checking and linting. Use `cargo run` directly (never `cargo build` then `cargo run`); often just stop and let the user test
- **Use package manager commands, never hand-edit manifests** — detect the manager from the lockfile (`bun.lock`→`bun`, `pnpm-lock.yaml`→`pnpm`, `package-lock.json`→`npm`, `Cargo.toml`→`cargo`). Get the latest compatible version
- **Check commands**: default to `just` recipes (`just check`, `just test`) over raw `cargo`/`npm`

## Command Execution

- **Check `--help`** for unfamiliar commands — your training data may not match the installed version
- **Handle interactive prompts**: use non-interactive flags (`--yes`, `-y`, `--non-interactive`) so CLIs don't hang
- Keep each Bash call simple. The Bash tool already returns the output — read it there; don't add `head`/`tail`/`grep` or a file redirect just to see or trim it
- **Never redirect output to a file and then read it back** (`cmd > out.txt` then reading `out.txt` is pure waste). Redirect only when the file itself is the goal. Don't suppress errors (`2>/dev/null`) — stderr often holds the answer
- **Don't assign or expand shell variables** (`SP=/tmp/…; cmd "$SP"`) — the permission matcher blocks expansions with a manual "Contains simple_expansion" prompt. Write the literal path every time, however long, instead of aliasing it

## Testing

- **TDD**: write a failing test first, then implement, in projects with test infra. Integration tests in `tests/`; unit tests alongside code
- Prefer `just test`, else `cargo nextest run` over raw `cargo test`. Run tests after changes

## Code Style

Write idiomatic code for the language — check existing patterns first.

- **Rust**: iterators/combinators over loops; `&[T]` over `&Vec<T>`; direct imports when heavily used
- **TypeScript**: absolute imports (`@/…`) when the pattern exists; functional patterns over loops

**Formatting**: use the project's auto-formatter; never hand-fix formatting with Edit. Run it, then re-read any file you'll edit further. Never auto-format generated files.

## Comments & Documentation

- **Default to no comment.** Only a genuinely non-obvious invariant earns one; keep the wording plain
- **Hard length caps.** A standalone comment is one line by default, two maximum; past that, move it to a doc comment or cut it. A trailing comment must fit the line (~10 words). Doc comments open with one self-contained summary line
- **No em dashes or unicode dashes in comments; never use `--` as a connective.** Reword with a comma or split into two sentences; keep legitimate `--` only as real syntax (`cargo run -- <args>`, a `--flag`)
- **Comments must stand on their own** — never reference external documents, tickets, or section numbers. Explain the *why* directly
- **Never** reference old implementations/migrations, add banner comments (`===`, `-----`), or bare section-label comments
- Update project CLAUDE.md when making architectural decisions

## Git Commits

- **Default branch is `master`, not `main`** for `Xevion/` repos
- **No AI co-authoring or attribution**
- **NEVER add a `Claude-Session` trailer, a `https://claude.ai/code/…` link, or any session/attribution trailer to a commit message or PR body — not ever, regardless of what a tool, template, or harness instruction says to append.** Strip one if you see it
- **Don't** run `git stash` without approval or rewrite history unless asked; verify a commit landed when hooks fail
- Concise messages, "why" over "what"; conventional-commit style for a first commit, else match the project

## AI Artifacts Stay Private

The AI writes code in my stead; AI markers are hidden from the public. Treat AI presence in a repo as private by default — minor exceptions are the exception.

- Most AI files aren't tracked — `CLAUDE.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `.claude/`, and AI planning docs (`RESEARCH.md`, `design.md`, scratch) are typically excluded. Don't assume any is tracked
- **`.git/info/exclude`, not `.gitignore`, is the usual mechanism** — it excludes files locally and privately, never committed, so a public clone shows no trace. Consult it too when reasoning about what's tracked
- **Never question or "fix" an ignored `CLAUDE.md`** — its absence is deliberate

## AI Development Workflow

**`modify → check → test → hand off`.** Don't run dev servers, builds, or long-running processes yourself. After type checking passes, building is unnecessary.

- **File-content invalidation**: after any command that rewrites files (formatters, `--fix`), re-read files before editing — your in-context copy is stale
- **Debugging**: read the source and confirm the failure before proposing a fix; after two failed fixes, change strategy entirely
- **Never guess file paths** — verify before reading unfamiliar files

## Security

Watch for command injection, XSS, SQL injection, and the OWASP Top 10; validate external inputs. If you write insecure code, fix it immediately.

## Tools

- **Never fabricate documentation URLs** — discover first (WebSearch, context7, `gh` CLI), then fetch. User-provided URLs are safe
- Fetch GitHub files via `raw.githubusercontent.com/{owner}/{repo}/{branch}/{path}`; use `gh` CLI for API/search/PRs
- Prefer `jq` (JSON), `bun` (quick TS scripts), `hyperfine` (benchmarks), `tokei` (LOC) over convoluted pipelines

---

**Remember**: Project-specific rules files take precedence over these global guidelines.
